These are exactly the kind of "Senior-level" keywords that will get you noticed! Here is the breakdown of what they mean and why they are powerful for your portfolio:

### 1. Idempotent (The "Safety Switch")
In Engineering, an **Idempotent** script is one that you can run 100 times, but it only changes the system the *first* time (or only when a change is actually needed).

*   **Real-world Analogy**: A **Light Switch**. If the light is already ON and you flip it to ON again, nothing happens. It stays in the desired state. (Compare this to a "Toggle" which is dangerous because it flips the state every time).
*   **In your project**: Your [task.ps1](cci:7://file:///c:/Users/along/PDBREng/de-lab-001-pandas-postgres-etl/task.ps1:0:0-0:0) and `init_db.ps1` scripts are idempotent. If you run `task.ps1 clean` and the tables are already gone, it doesn't crash—it just confirms they aren't there. If you run a setup script twice, it doesn't create duplicate databases.
*   **Why it's "Senior"**: Juniors write scripts that only work once. Seniors write scripts that are safe to run in automated CI/CD pipelines without breaking things.

### 2. GX Gates (The "Data Police")
**GX** stands for **Great Expectations**, which is the industry-standard tool for "Unit Testing" your data.

*   **Real-world Analogy**: A **Factory Inspector** on a production line. If a cereal box comes through half-empty, the inspector pulls it off the line before it reaches the customer.
*   **In your project**: We used "Physics Quality Gates." For example, if an IoT sensor sends a temperature of 500°C (which is impossible for our equipment), the **GX Gate** catches it. Instead of letting that "poison" your dashboard metrics, it diverts that record to a **Quarantine** table.
*   **Why it's "Senior"**: It shows you don't just "move" data; you **guard** the quality of the data. You aren't just an engineer; you are a Reliability expert.

### 3. Executive Watchtower (The "Command Center")
